1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,760
In this video, we will cover the core of how transformer models work.

2

00:00:04,760  -->  00:00:07,140
Specifically, we will look into how

3

00:00:07,140  -->  00:00:11,605
the attention mechanism is implemented in transformers.

4

00:00:11,605  -->  00:00:16,790
To remind you, transformer models consist of multiple blocks.

5

00:00:16,790  -->  00:00:20,430
Every block refines the embedding vectors for each

6

00:00:20,430  -->  00:00:24,570
token using the context of other embedding vectors.

7

00:00:24,570  -->  00:00:28,690
The way this is done is that an attention block first computes

8

00:00:28,690  -->  00:00:32,350
attention scores and then updates

9

00:00:32,350  -->  00:00:36,930
embedding values in each position using these attention scores.

10

00:00:36,930  -->  00:00:41,170
Let's now look at how it is implemented step by step.

11

00:00:41,170  -->  00:00:46,270
The first step in the attention block is to calculate a so called query matrix.

12

00:00:46,270  -->  00:00:49,310
The way this is done is we take the matrix with

13

00:00:49,310  -->  00:00:55,895
embedding vectors and multiply it by another matrix called W_Q.

14

00:00:55,895  -->  00:00:59,890
It will produce a matrix with the same number of vectors,

15

00:00:59,890  -->  00:01:04,210
but each vector will have a different smaller dimension.

16

00:01:04,210  -->  00:01:08,530
This matrix is called queries or Q for short.

17

00:01:08,530  -->  00:01:13,360
To make it easier, we will represent the queries matrix like this.

18

00:01:13,360  -->  00:01:17,590
Where instead of displaying every value in this matrix,

19

00:01:17,590  -->  00:01:22,970
we will just display an array of vectors for the Q matrix.

20

00:01:23,050  -->  00:01:26,550
In addition to computing the Q matrix,

21

00:01:26,550  -->  00:01:30,810
we need to compute another matrix called keys.

22

00:01:31,580  -->  00:01:34,300
We do it in a similar way.

23

00:01:34,300  -->  00:01:40,905
We take inputting embedding vectors and multiply them by another matrix called W_Q,

24

00:01:40,905  -->  00:01:45,740
which produces the keys matrix or key for short.

25

00:01:45,830  -->  00:01:50,190
What are the conceptual roles of these matrices?

26

00:01:50,190  -->  00:01:53,490
We can think of them as if queries are asking

27

00:01:53,490  -->  00:01:57,170
questions about other words in the sentence.

28

00:01:57,170  -->  00:02:01,170
For example, those could be nouns looking for verbs,

29

00:02:01,170  -->  00:02:05,250
and vectors in this matrix represent these questions,

30

00:02:05,250  -->  00:02:10,610
and the role of the keys is to answer these questions asked by queries.

31

00:02:10,610  -->  00:02:12,210
Having these two matrices,

32

00:02:12,210  -->  00:02:16,510
we should find out what keys match to what queries.

33

00:02:16,510  -->  00:02:20,490
To represent this in terms of matrix multiplications,

34

00:02:20,490  -->  00:02:25,180
we would look for what queries are most similar to what keys.

35

00:02:25,180  -->  00:02:28,200
We already know how to do this for vectors.

36

00:02:28,200  -->  00:02:31,320
We can do this by computing a dot product between

37

00:02:31,320  -->  00:02:35,100
each pair of vectors in Q and K matrices.

38

00:02:35,100  -->  00:02:37,900
The larger the value of each dot product,

39

00:02:37,900  -->  00:02:42,120
the more similar a pair of a key and the query is.

40

00:02:42,120  -->  00:02:45,480
What we want to do is to compute dot products

41

00:02:45,480  -->  00:02:49,460
between each pair of vectors in matrices Q and K,

42

00:02:49,460  -->  00:02:52,945
and this will result in another matrix.

43

00:02:52,945  -->  00:02:55,750
If you remember your linear algebra,

44

00:02:55,750  -->  00:02:57,910
this should sound very familiar.

45

00:02:57,910  -->  00:03:02,470
To compute a pairwise product between vectors in two matrices,

46

00:03:02,470  -->  00:03:05,310
we need to multiply these two matrices,

47

00:03:05,310  -->  00:03:11,410
and we also need to transpose the K matrix to make sure that dimensions match.

48

00:03:11,410  -->  00:03:14,750
The result matrix will contain the attention scores.

49

00:03:14,750  -->  00:03:17,570
However, one issue we discussed before

50

00:03:17,570  -->  00:03:21,590
is that dot product can result in pretty much any value.

51

00:03:21,590  -->  00:03:24,650
Before we can use these attention scores,

52

00:03:24,650  -->  00:03:26,470
we need to convert them.

53

00:03:26,470  -->  00:03:29,290
What we want to do is we want to make sure that

54

00:03:29,290  -->  00:03:32,645
the sum of each column should equal to one,

55

00:03:32,645  -->  00:03:35,950
and the greater the dot product result is,

56

00:03:35,950  -->  00:03:39,960
the greater the result value in this column should be.

57

00:03:39,960  -->  00:03:42,450
If you recall, we've already discussed that we

58

00:03:42,450  -->  00:03:45,930
can use the softmax function just for this.

59

00:03:45,930  -->  00:03:49,830
What we will do is we'll pass every column

60

00:03:49,830  -->  00:03:54,020
of this resulting matrix through the softmax function.

61

00:03:54,020  -->  00:03:58,900
Now, all values in each column will be between zero and one,

62

00:03:58,900  -->  00:04:01,130
and they will sum up to one.

63

00:04:01,130  -->  00:04:04,330
To help you to keep track of what we've done so far,

64

00:04:04,330  -->  00:04:09,520
I'll show a small diagram of all operations we've already covered.

65

00:04:09,520  -->  00:04:13,750
We first take the input matrix, with embedding vectors,

66

00:04:13,750  -->  00:04:15,690
and then from the same input,

67

00:04:15,690  -->  00:04:17,870
we want to get two matrices,

68

00:04:17,870  -->  00:04:24,745
Q and K. We then perform a matrix multiplication between these two matrices,

69

00:04:24,745  -->  00:04:28,275
and we apply the softmax function.

70

00:04:28,275  -->  00:04:34,720
This results in the attention scores we can now use to update the embedding vectors.

71

00:04:34,720  -->  00:04:39,140
To do this, we need to take the values of another matrix called V,

72

00:04:39,140  -->  00:04:45,240
which we get in a similar way to how we got the matrices Q and K. Then we'll

73

00:04:45,240  -->  00:04:51,410
multiply each vector in this matrix by the corresponding attention scores.

74

00:04:51,410  -->  00:04:54,560
This multiplication of the V vectors by

75

00:04:54,560  -->  00:04:59,775
this scores will give us a new embedding vector in every single position.

76

00:04:59,775  -->  00:05:04,020
Specifically, to compute a new vector for Position 2,

77

00:05:04,020  -->  00:05:07,550
we take the V_1 vector from the V matrix.

78

00:05:07,550  -->  00:05:12,860
We multiply it by this 0.046 score,

79

00:05:12,860  -->  00:05:15,490
then we get the V_2 vector,

80

00:05:15,490  -->  00:05:19,270
we multiply it by the second score, and so on.

81

00:05:19,270  -->  00:05:22,590
The weighted sum of all these vectors given

82

00:05:22,590  -->  00:05:26,845
the attention scores is a new embedding vector for Position 2,

83

00:05:26,845  -->  00:05:30,260
and we do this for all vectors in all positions.

84

00:05:30,260  -->  00:05:35,930
Now, we can draw a complete diagram of computations in the attention block.

85

00:05:35,930  -->  00:05:38,650
First, we compute matrices Q, K,

86

00:05:38,650  -->  00:05:44,580
and V from input embedding vectors by multiplying them by different matrices.

87

00:05:44,580  -->  00:05:48,190
We then multiply Q and K matrices

88

00:05:48,190  -->  00:05:52,910
and use the softmax function to compute the attention scores.

89

00:05:52,910  -->  00:05:55,830
After this, we use the attention scores and

90

00:05:55,830  -->  00:06:00,345
the V matrix to get the updated embedding vectors.

91

00:06:00,345  -->  00:06:02,740
In models like GPT,

92

00:06:02,740  -->  00:06:05,865
we don't calculate attention scores just once.

93

00:06:05,865  -->  00:06:09,680
What we've covered was a so called a single-head of attention.

94

00:06:09,680  -->  00:06:16,620
Instead, this process is split in multiple similar computations or attention heads.

95

00:06:16,620  -->  00:06:21,020
They do the same computations but with different parameters.

96

00:06:21,020  -->  00:06:25,280
This is done because the words in a sentence can relate in different ways,

97

00:06:25,280  -->  00:06:27,780
and having multiple-heads calculating

98

00:06:27,780  -->  00:06:32,500
separate attention scores allow us to learn different relationships.

99

00:06:32,500  -->  00:06:36,520
Each attention head outputs part of the result embedding vectors,

100

00:06:36,520  -->  00:06:41,115
and we then concatenate them together to form new embedding vectors.

101

00:06:41,115  -->  00:06:44,260
Now, once we've covered how the attention is calculated,

102

00:06:44,260  -->  00:06:48,980
we can wrap up this video by looking at the formula of the attention.

103

00:06:48,980  -->  00:06:53,480
We'll get this formula straight from the attention is all you need paper.

104

00:06:53,480  -->  00:06:57,255
The attention is a formula of three matrices: Q,

105

00:06:57,255  -->  00:07:01,480
K, and V. We've covered most of what it does.

106

00:07:01,480  -->  00:07:05,500
We multiply matrices Q and K. One

107

00:07:05,500  -->  00:07:09,340
thing we didn't cover yet is that we then divide the result by

108

00:07:09,340  -->  00:07:12,565
the square root of the size of a vector in matrix

109

00:07:12,565  -->  00:07:18,240
K. This is done to ensure that attention scores don't get too large.

110

00:07:18,240  -->  00:07:23,795
We then apply the softmax function to calculate the attention scores.

111

00:07:23,795  -->  00:07:28,020
Then we multiply the result by the V matrix.

112

00:07:28,020  -->  00:07:32,665
I have to say it's a very short and concise way of representing this,

113

00:07:32,665  -->  00:07:36,480
but I hope that once you went through these steps one by one,

114

00:07:36,480  -->  00:07:40,060
this formula now makes more sense.
